article.headline: (23) MARQUETTE 75, VALPARAISO 70
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Travis Diener scored 26 points, including a key driving layup with 23 seconds left, and No. 23 Marquette rallied to beat Valparaiso 75-70 Saturday night in the Blue & Gold Classic. It is the fifth consecutive year Marquette (3-0) has won its early-season tournament, coinciding with the arrival of coach Tom Crean. Valparaiso (1-1) scored the first 11 points, but missed four free throws in the final 49 seconds. Roberto Nieves, who had 17 points, hit a 3-pointer to bring the Crusaders to 70-69 with 1:43 left. Scott Merritt, who had 16 points and 10 rebounds, made a pair of free throws to build Marquette's lead to 72-69 with 1:05 to go. Ali Berdiel then missed the front end of a one-and-one with 49 seconds left, and Diener drove the lane and scored to give the Golden Eagles a 74-69 lead. Berdiel was fouled and missed two more free throws with 16 seconds to go. Marquette's Steve Novak and Valparaiso's Ron Howard hit a free throw apiece in the last 14 seconds for the final score. Diener, averaging 19.3 points, had nine assists and only two turnovers and was named Most Valuable Player of the tournament. Dan Oppland made a pair of free throws to give the Crusaders a 62-61 lead with 5:36 left. Diener then hit a 15-foot jumper to give the Golden Eagles the lead for good at 63-62. The Crusaders' Ali Berdiel missed the front end of a one-and-one, and Scott Merritt picked up a loose ball and scored on a layup to give Marquette a 65-62 lead with 4:34 left. Valparaiso took 11-0 lead in the first two minutes behind two 3-pointers by Nieves and one by Howard, a sophomore who spent his freshman season at Marquette. Marquette had given up only two 3s in each of its first two games, but the Crusaders made six in the first 11:25 against the Golden Eagles. Marquette didn't take its first lead until Diener converted a three-point play to give the Golden Eagles a 39-38 lead with 16:22 left in game. The lead then changed hands 12 times, and there were five ties before Marquette took the lead for good.
